\begin_layout Subsection
Communication overhead
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stripe-wise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stripe-wise is the simplest one.
 So there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vertices in each direction.
 So, for every boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vertices have to be communicated in each direction, yielding about 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 doubles.
 Every double is 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 bytes, so there are 
\begin_inset Formula $16n$
\end_inset

 bytes communicated per boundary.
 We have on less boundary than the number of processes, so 
\begin_inset Formula $P-1$
\end_inset

 boundaries.
 That makes the total amount of data communicated: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Bytes communicated}=16\cdot n\cdot(P-1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Block-wise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the block-wise layout, we shall assume that the number of processes
 is a perfect square.
 The boundaries still form a line and the number of bytes that have to be
 communicated per boundary is almost the same as in the stripe-wise case
 (which was 
\begin_inset Formula $16n$
\end_inset

), because now we also need to take into account that we have to communicate
 a few points diagonally as well.
 The number of boundaries is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sqrt{P}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 in each direction.
 And we have to communicate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sqrt{P}-1\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 points back and forth between diagonal neighbors, which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $16\cdot(p-2\sqrt{p}+1)$
\end_inset

 bytes.
 Therefore the total number of bytes communicated is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Bytes communicated}=16\cdot\left(n\cdot\left(\sqrt{P}-1\right)+\left(p-2\sqrt{p}+1\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

