\begin_layout Standard
We clearly see that if the problem is small, the overhead of using the GPU
 is so large that using the GPU is many times slower than using the CPU.
 However, when the problem size becomes bigger, the performance gain of
 using the GPU outweighs the overhead of getting the data into the GPU and
 we start seeing great speedups, up to 20 times.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, when we do not take the overhead of copying memory between the
 CPU and the GPU into account and only time the actual computation time,
 we see that the GPU is many many times faster than the CPU, especially
 on the bigger problems.
 With speedups of up to 700 times.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though this is an amazing speedup.
 I think it is fairest to compare the total execution time of the two methods.
 As that will be the time that you will actually have to wait for the program
 to complete.
 Which is gonna be the left half of the table.
\end_layout

