\end_inset

 we can see that the overhead involved in calling GPU functions is quite
 significant, in fact so significant that for small problems using the GPU
 is much slower than simply using the CPU.
 However, as the GPU is so much faster at doing the actual computations,
 as the problem size grows the overhead of copying the memory to the GPU
 is becoming less important and we get a speed of bout 19 times the speed
 of the CPU.
 Which is very significant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
GPU with shared memory and without memory copy overhead
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If we ignore the start-time of the GPU and the time it takes to copy the
 memory between the CPU and GPU, we see that we can actually have a speed-boost
 of about 700 times for the larger cases, which is incredible.
 I looked up the specs of the GPU and CPU of the DAS-cluster, and from that
 I would expect a speed-up of about 480 times.
 If we look at the computations in global memory, then we see such speedups,
 so I guess the improvements come from a very efficient memory usage and
 the clever vector sum algorithm present in the provided code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
GPU with global memory
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The code of the GPU without shared memory was much much simpler than the
 code with the shared memory.
 It did not need the rather hard to follow memory copy stuff.
 The actual computations were about 2-3 times slower compared to the optimized
 code with __shared__ memory, so we do indeed see that the shared memory
 was indeed much faster to access than the global memory.
 However, as the computation was only a small fraction of the time the entire
 GPU algorithm took, the total time was marginally slower (if we include
 the memory copy times).
 So, if I ever were to program on a GPU I would use global memory unless
 the computation time is significantly longer than the time to copy the
 vectors back and forth.
\end_layout

